<taxonomicName id="1FAE4AF6DB72AE58720764DFBC73DEE2" LSID="http://species-id.net/wiki/Platyphora_selva" authority="Daccordi, 1994" authorityName="Daccordi" authorityYear="1994" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platyphora selva" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="selva">Platyphora selva Daccordi, 1994</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="24BA761D3D53786FA9ABC097D3E32752" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="77" pageId="5" pageNumber="76" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="8C392667988D3829F2439FA129890E05" pageId="5" pageNumber="76">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3E3C39CF5156CE5D4585F9C655887666" pageId="5" pageNumber="76">
Within New World 
<taxonomicName id="E2320052042B49477D6A590A67B2DA1C" lsidName="" pageId="5" pageNumber="76" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chrysomelinae">Chrysomelinae</taxonomicName>
, reports of subsociality until recently were limited to a single species studied at the La Selva Field station in the Atlantic lowlands of Costa Rica (
<bibRefCitation id="CF0DABF15C979A09564CC3BBBF16DFD7" author="Choe, JC" journalOrPublisher="Psyche" pageId="14" pageNumber="85" pagination="63 - 68" title="Maternal care in Labidomera suturella Chevrolat (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae: Chrysomelinae) from Costa Rica." url="10.1155/1989/62318" volume="96" year="1989">Choe 1989</bibRefCitation>
). However a misidentification of that species (not by the author) lead to erroneous attribution of subsocial behavior to 
<taxonomicName id="FE507BD18AB1D3D0F9323266105F87DD" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Labidomera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Labidomera suturalis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="suturalis">Labidomera suturalis</taxonomicName>
, rather than to an unidentified species of 
<taxonomicName id="1AD04C465B97C913E449B125F9A0E537" authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platyphora" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Platyphora</taxonomicName>
. The species was subsequently described and named 
<taxonomicName id="002768A299CFB3E6268DA93B689AB069" authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platyphora selva" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="selva">Platyphora selva</taxonomicName>
by Daccordi without comments on 
<normalizedToken id="AB9F5D45F9DC5F0978B442C2AE663672" originalValue="Choe’s">Choe's</normalizedToken>
behavioral observations (
<bibRefCitation id="3FDCBBE29AADD65F23B31005587040C4" author="Daccordi, M" journalOrPublisher="Memorie della Societa Entomologica Italiana" pageId="15" pageNumber="86" pagination="221 - 232" title="Nuove specie di Platyphora della regione neotropicale (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae, Chrysomelinae)." volume="72" year="1993">Daccordi 1993</bibRefCitation>
). As noted by 
<bibRefCitation id="8140BD251D9D400E553A7848ABD7B94A" author="Reid, CAM" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="16" pageNumber="87" pagination="373 - 398" title="The morphology and biology of Pterodunga mirabile Daccordi, an unusual subsocial Chrysomeline (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae)." url="10.1080/00222930802586016" volume="43" year="2009">Reid et al. (2009)</bibRefCitation>
, this first record of subsocial behavior in Neotropical chrysomelines led to a number of reports citing the original paper and repeating the taxonomic error (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="D100B502E26D258EBDB742C428B07623" author="Windsor, DM" editor="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="Annual Review of Entomology" pageId="17" pageNumber="88" title="Kluwer Academic Publishers, Dordrecht, The Netherlands" url="10.1007/978-94-011-1781-4_4" year="1994">Windsor and Choe 1994</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="356538AD9B85772703556B27DA2107AD" pageId="5" pageNumber="76">
<normalizedToken id="2ADE876ED7D1F96B5BDDC2A7F74C3AFA" originalValue="Kudô">Kudo</normalizedToken>
and Hasegawa 2003
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="1C52F7EB2115A3806683AE4E5E174818" author="Costa, JT" journalOrPublisher="Belknap Press of Harvard University Press, Cambridge, MA" pageId="15" pageNumber="86" title="The other insect societies." year="2006">Costa 2006</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="77EA3AE30A33B36C09DE06DDE345589E" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="77" pageId="5" pageNumber="76">
<bibRefCitation id="9EF7ACBD10F52BC5404BBD2BDC919344" author="Choe, JC" journalOrPublisher="Psyche" pageId="14" pageNumber="85" pagination="63 - 68" title="Maternal care in Labidomera suturella Chevrolat (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae: Chrysomelinae) from Costa Rica." url="10.1155/1989/62318" volume="96" year="1989">Choe (1989)</bibRefCitation>
observed 18 guarding 
<taxonomicName id="45F85018E6776264D645877DAEF8BE3E" authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platyphora selva" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="selva">
<pageBreakToken id="25EEBA525BDA331D8B5D779CDEE70DD9" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" start="start">Platyphora</pageBreakToken>
selva
</taxonomicName>
females in two different years, all feeding on 
<taxonomicName id="25D6F2A4053441E330F2B2BB8204C201" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Lycianthes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lycianthes (Witheringia) heteroclita" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="heteroclita" subGenus="Witheringia">Lycianthes (Witheringia) heteroclita</taxonomicName>
Sendtm. (
<taxonomicName id="1BDA9216BB7736EE231F30B2FA6E6C59" genus="Solanaceae" lsidName="Solanaceae" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" rank="genus">Solanaceae</taxonomicName>
) in the Atlantic lowlands of Costa Rica. His observations were remarkable in first describing how females of this species tightly guarded offspring by straddling. By removing mothers from roughly half of the families, he was able to demonstrate that guarding was highly effective in preventing predation by the gigantic ponerine ant, 
<taxonomicName id="7B340140A249A20210D1FF8B40712BE7" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Paraponera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paraponera clavata" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="clavata">Paraponera clavata</taxonomicName>
Fab. The importance of maternal defenses in reducing losses to parasitoids, however, was not investigated. Further, it was noted that mothers always guarded groups of four or fewer larvae; but eggs of the beetle were never observed during the study. From observations of related taxa (see below) we now suspect that 
<taxonomicName id="83C9F0E396D171C14822C8693FAD6B50" authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platyphora selva" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="selva">Platyphora selva</taxonomicName>
is not oviparous, but instead deposits temporally isolated clutches of four larvae. This inference remains to be documented and is based on the habits of the morphologically similar species, 
<taxonomicName id="C8746A5B2C7A2C19FBDA92B90CB0EEB2" authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platyphora microspina" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="microspina">Platyphora microspina</taxonomicName>
, which occurs widely (but rarely) in neighboring Panama. Regrettably, sequence data are not yet available for 
<taxonomicName id="210314D99CA754BB372902C3F8073E08" authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platyphora selva" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="selva">Platyphora selva</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
